normal limits. The physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the changes seen on the X-ray?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lymphoma","Right lower lobe collapse","Carcinoma of the lung","Goitre","Right-sided pneumothorax"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray in this case shows deviation of the trachea to the right and a paratracheal mass, which is most likely to be a \u003Cstrong\u003Egoitre\u003C/strong\u003E. Goitres are enlargements of the thyroid gland that can extend into the superior mediastinum and cause tracheal deviation. In an asymptomatic elderly patient with no other concerning features, a goitre is the most probable benign cause of these radiographic findings.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present as a mediastinal mass and cause tracheal deviation. However, lymphoma typically presents with systemic symptoms such as fever, night sweats, and weight loss, which are not present in this case. Additionally, lymphoma is less common than goitre in this age group.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight lower lobe collapse\u003C/strong\u003E would not typically cause superior mediastinal widening or tracheal deviation to the right. Lobar collapse usually causes volume loss and shift of mediastinal structures towards the affected side, which is not seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the lung\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in any elderly patient with an abnormal chest X-ray. However, lung cancer typically presents with symptoms such as cough, hemoptysis, or weight loss. The absence of symptoms and the patient\u0027s non-smoking status make this less likely than a benign goitre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumothorax\u003C/strong\u003E can cause tracheal deviation, but it typically deviates the trachea away from the affected side. A right-sided pneumothorax would push the trachea to the left, not to the right as seen in this image. Additionally, a pneumothorax would present with acute symptoms and would be visible as a lucency on the chest X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s age, gender, asymptomatic presentation, and the radiographic findings, a goitre is the most likely explanation for the changes seen on the X-ray. Further evaluation with thyroid function tests and possibly a CT scan or ultrasound of the neck would be appropriate to confirm the diagnosis and assess the extent of the goitre.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Goitre can cause tracheal deviation on chest X-ray, appearing as a paratracheal mass in the superior mediastinum.","Asymptomatic tracheal deviation in an elderly patient should prompt consideration of benign causes such as goitre before assuming malignancy.","Chest X-ray interpretation should include assessment of tracheal position and mediastinal contours."],"references":["Takamori T, Izawa S, Fukuhara T, et al. Clinical Characteristics and Predictors Related to the Progression of Multinodular Goiter Causing Tracheal Compression and Deviation: A Report of Two Cases and Review of the Literature. Intern Med 2022; 61:1375-81."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86358"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21086"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21086"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2mPP4ZswBdLua9JVELoGGtCGdRAGz8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2mPP4ZswBdLua9JVELoGGtCGdRAGz8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":812,"height":585}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86358","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86